<DOC><DOCNO> AP880520-0259 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2114EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-20 0482</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0495</SECOND><HEAD>Severe Storms Precede Cold Front in Nation's Midsection</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A western cold front spawned thunderstorms, high winds and hailover most of the Great Plains and central United States Friday,while the rain-saturated East Coast got still more precipitation.   Severe thunderstorms blanketed the Great Plains, with clustersof showers over central Texas, northern Oklahoma and southernKansas, as well as eastern Nebraska to southwest Minnesota.   Residents in Hobbs, N.M., reported seeing two tornadoes touchdown Friday. One twister tore part of the roof and a side from abuilding, uprooted trees, knocked down telephone poles andoverturned a pickup truck, slightly injuring the driver. The secondtornado destroyed an unoccupied mobile home, and tore off parts ofthe roofs of two houses, a witness said.   The storm system brought golf ball-sized hail at Hunt andKerrville, Texas, and marble-sized hail near El Dorado, Kan.   Showers over the central High Plains and southern and centralRockies were accompanied by blustery north winds gusting to 40 mph,sending the mercury plunging into the 40s and 50s.   Rain and drizzly weather continued in the Northeast, with severestorms stretching from Maryland to eastern North Carolina duringthe afternoon and evening.   In Pennsylvania, where 8 inches of rain have fallen in parts ofthe state since Monday, a 16-year-old youth drowned Thursday nightwhile rafting with some friends on a rain-swollen creek inFayetteville, state police said.   The heavy rains have caused creeks and streams to overflow, aswell as minor flooding in low-lying areas.   Southwestern and eastern Pennsylvania, parts of eastern New Yorkstate, northern and western New Jersey, northern Delaware, northernand central Maryland, northern Virginia and the eastern Panhandleof West Virginia had all issued flood watches through the evening.   Sunny skies prevailed west of the Rockies and in the Southeast.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38degrees at Limon, Colo., to 100 at Palm Springs, Calif. The morninglow for the nation was 19 degrees in West Yellowstone, Mont.   Saturday's forecast called for showers and thunderstormsstretching from New England to the upper Ohio Valley, Virginia andeastern North Carolina and from the southern Plains throughout thecentral Plains and the lower Missouri Valley to the upperMississippi Valley, with rain heaviest over Oklahoma and northwestTexas. Sunny skies were predicted for the rest of the nation.   High temperatures should remain below 70 in the central HighPlains and the central Rockies, with highs only in the 50s ineastern Colorado and southeastern Wyoming, and in the 60s innorthern Minnesota, as well as southern and eastern New England.Highs should rise into the 80s west of the Rockies and in the SouthAtlantic Coast, reaching into the 90s from southern Arizona throughsouthern Nevada and western California into southwestern Oregon,topping 100 in desert areas of California and Arizona.</TEXT></DOC>